<br>
Just some thoughts in no particular order, numbered for ease of reading.<br>
<br>
1.  I think what he was referring to as being ridiculed was being called a loser that works in a cubicle all day, or something to that effect.  I know, I know.  It is hard to imagine name-calling with the high level of discourse this thread has seen.  Smiley faces with tongues out might be seen as ridicule too. I try to be objective, and I hope I don't offend anyone.<br>
<br>
2.  You are right.  There is a line between complaining and discussing.  There is also a line between being objective and cursing/name-calling.  So perhaps you should address forum etiquette with some of the other posters as well.<br>
<br>
3.  Yes, I too find the level of whining/griping disturbing on the boards, but there is much useful information here as well.  Also, take a look at some of the boards for other classes.  I read them sometimes for fun.  If you think Magicians gripe, you haven't seen anything yet.  <br>
<br>
4.  I have yet to see a response to my question about twinking and why it is less of a blow to the integrity of the game than the thought of someone buying planar gear.  Clearly it is not that someone worked for planar gear.  Someone worked for the SMR the level 1 mage is wearing too.<br>
<br>
5.  Why do people keep saying fq2010 should join a large guild.  I think he made it clear that he didn't want to do so.  His reasons are his own.  Respect his choice.  <br>
<br>
After dieing three times the other night because of a failed quest Afterlife tried, I can see how some people may have ill feelings towards the really large guilds.  In their defense they were trying to rez people that died as a result, but the idea that quests can effect those not directly involved is sort of scary.  <br>
<br>
Think of it this way.  If you aren't in said guild, you can reap no rewards for any quests/raids they complete/go on, but it is possible that you will suffer ill effects due to the quests/raids.<br>
<br>
6.  I don't think fq2010 ever implied that EQ should cater to those who solo, merely that it shouldn't cater only to those in large guilds.  It should be fun/rewarding for those in big guilds, small guilds, no guilds, or even soloists.  All pay money which keeps the game going.  Too many people forget that.  <br>
<br>
Yes it is a massive multi-player game, but if the true intent were for everyone to work together, I think many guilds would be much more open than they are.  You wouldn't see guilds with a table of classes by desirability.  (Also, allowing for more than 6 people per group would encourage team work as well.  This is not the place to discuss that though).<br>
<br>
Well, those are my thoughts.  Flame if you must.<br>
<br>
Copperrfield<br>
